name: Kamlabai Sea Food Restaurant

reviews.review_text: The restaurant is located in a quiet area and there is no dedicated parking, but one can park on the road. It is very popular with the locals. The place is very basic and one should avoid the closed portion as it is very noisy. The food is another story. We had chonak fry, liver masala, fried prawns, chicken masala, prawn pulao and nans. All well dishes were superb and the portions were good. Pricing is quite reasonable and the service was very quick. The bar service is just about ok and they had limited quantity of feni- this is an absolute no-no for a Goan restaurant. Do not go for the decor or atmosphere- the food makes up for the lack thereof. Definitely a place to try out some genuine seafood. The place is closed on Thursdays. For wheelchair guests, there are two steps for which the staff can assist.

I used to visit here 10 years back when I was residing in Goa. It was the best back than too. I recently visited it again and to my surprise, it was still as lovely!! The food is pure, authentic Goan style and pocket friendly. It's a great place to visit with family.

There was a time I was recommending people to visit kamlabai restaurant for fish , but now I won't ever

Today I visited at around 3.30 pm
Timing was unusual but still waiter were nice
Atmosphere was nice
I wanted kingfish thali,  but they didn't had it , so ordered modso thali & also ordered chicken 65 and a reshad bangdo
And fish taste wasn't even close to good
Modso#burso
Bangdo#burso
Chicken 65 was good
Rest things in thali were good , like tisro, Suki sungta kismoor that was tasty
But I won't ever recommend fish items in this resturant
One more thing I don't get is
For water bottles the MRP is 20 rs and still most of restaurants are charging 30 rs

description:
**Kamlabai Sea Food Restaurant: A Hidden Gem in Mapusa**

Nestled in the serene locale of Mapusa, Kamlabai Sea Food Restaurant boasts an inviting rating of 3.8 from an impressive 4,700 reviews. The establishment is primarily celebrated for its authentic Goan seafood, with standout offerings like "thali" (185 mentions), "goan" (140 mentions), king fish (38 mentions), and prawn curry (13 mentions) making it a much-favored dining destination among locals and visitors alike. 

**Ambiance & Design**
Entering Kamlabai, diners are immediately enveloped by a straightforward, no-frills d√©cor that signifies the restaurant's focus on food over ostentation. The lighting is bright enough to illuminate the dishes yet subdued enough to create a comfortable space for meals. One review notes the challenge of noise from the closed-off section of the restaurant, suggesting a mix of bustling activity and cozy corners. Unfortunately, there are no dedicated parking facilities, but public roadside parking is available for diners. A key insight for guests is that accessibility may require a bit of assistance due to two steps leading to the main dining area.

**Menu & Culinary Experience**
The menu at Kamlabai highlights the quintessential flavors of Goa, with numerous reviews praising the generous portion sizes and value for money. The signature dishes, particularly the thali, deliver a hearty assortment of local fare, including prawn pulao, liver masala, and chicken masala, as well as various fish specialties. One guest reminisced about a prior visit ten years ago, affirming that while the ambiance may remain basic, the authenticity of the food continues to shine through. Some reviews suggest a decline in the quality of certain seafood options, like the kingfish, while other items, such as the chicken 65, were reported as exceptions worthy of praise. 

Visual elements from customer photos reveal vibrant plates filled with traditional Goan delights. For instance, images showcase well-presented thalis brimming with diverse offerings, while the hearty fried fish sits enticingly, awaiting enthusiastic diners. 

**Customer Experience & Service**
Customer service at Kamlabai appears to strike a balance of efficiency and friendliness. Several patrons remarked on the staff's pleasant demeanor despite an influx of customers. Although the bar service is rated as "just about okay," the overall wait staff seem ready to assist with any dining needs. Guests should be aware, however, of the restaurant's closure on Thursdays, and the atypical nature of their hours might influence when to visit.

**Popularity & Reviews**
Kamlabai has grown into a beloved spot for seafood lovers in the region, with local patrons keeping the buzz alive through their encouraging, if sometimes critical, online presence. While the sentiment leans positive, cautionary tales from regulars highlight individual experiences that may vary. Despite occasional criticisms regarding specific dishes, there seems to be a strong sentiment recommending the restaurant for its authentic Goan offerings.

**Utilizing Visual Content**
Images shared by customers serve to enhance the narrative beautifully, with mouthwatering visuals of thalis displaying colorful curries and fried dishes. Notable highlights include a decadent-looking prawn curry and an array of fried items that capture the essence of Kamlabai's culinary offerings. 

In conclusion, Kamlabai Sea Food Restaurant stands as a testament to the age-old Goan culinary tradition. While guests should temper their expectations regarding ambiance and certain seafood dishes, the heart of Kamlabai beats strong with quality food that reflects the rich tapestry of Goan cuisine. For anyone eager to experience genuine local seafood, Kamlabai undeniably warrants a visit.
